{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1784142485,"nonce":"1tD6nBDxVLCpFktzt7TdjX9RLLI=","kind":"spec","title":"Quarantine review ŌĆö sub-project A: namespace + item model + park-on-write (design)"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1784142485,"nonce":"8VMp96ZKfhMjWXlvAp8ocs1Nl4w=","body":"# Quarantine review ŌĆö sub-project A: namespace + item model + park-on-write (design)\n\nStatus: design approved 2026-07-15 (Trevor). Sub-project of the quarantine-review\narc; parent design `kref show 4cb93aef7611`. This spec covers ONLY A. B (review +\napprove/reject + replay) and C (surfaces) are separate own-cycle sub-projects.\n\n## Scope\n\nA flagged write (a body/comment tripping betterleaks on a syncable tier) is\nDIVERTED into a reserved holding namespace as a review-ready item, with its\nin-context review thread opened ŌĆö instead of being refused. A stops there:\nnothing is applied to the live target, and approve/reject/replay is B.\n\nDeliverable: after A, every flagged write across all six boundaries lands in the\n`quarantine` namespace with enough payload for B to apply it, and a reviewer can\nsee (via the thread) that a review is pending. `entryguard`/`commentguard` keep\nscanning; their OUTCOME changes from refuse to park.\n\n## A.1 The `quarantine` namespace\n\nA new reserved, private-typed built-in tier `quarantine` (`refs/kref-quarantine/`):\n\n- Added to `reservedTierNames`; not selectable as a write target and not a valid\n  custom-tier type.\n- Private-typed =\u003e non-syncable by construction (never pushed; push already skips\n  private, and must also skip quarantine).\n- Hidden from `kref tier list` and from normal entry listings (a system tier);\n  reachable only through the quarantine surfaces (built in C) and by direct id.\n- Writes into it are allowed by the secret policy (private tier =\u003e no scan), so\n  parking a secret-bearing payload cannot re-trigger parking (no recursion).\n\nBecause it is private-typed, quarantine items are host-local: they never merge\nacross machines. Each host has its own review queue; only APPROVED writes\n(replayed onto syncable entries in B) travel via normal DAG pull.\n\n## A.2 Item model ŌĆö two natural forms, one namespace\n\nHeld-write is stored as INTENT and replayed on approval (B) through the normal\nstore write path, so CAS, the write-lock, provenance, and every normal guard run\nat apply-time and an approved write looks exactly like a fresh human write.\n\n- New entry (`kref_remember` / `kref new`): born as a real draft entry in\n  `quarantine` with its proposed kind/title/body/content-type, plus a reserved\n  `q-dest:\u003ctier\u003e` label naming its intended destination tier. The review thread\n  is anchored on the draft. Approve (B) = `retier` the draft to `\u003ctier\u003e` ŌĆö the id\n  and the review thread travel with it. (A fresh create on approval would orphan\n  the thread; retier preserves it. This is why new entries are draft-native.)\n\n- Update / patch / comment on a live syncable entry: a `kind:quarantine`\n  intent-item whose body is a structured JSON record:\n  `{schema, target_id, op_kind: set-body|add-comment, content, comment: {question?,\n  reply_to?}, author, actor_kind, time}`. The live target is untouched and stays\n  syncable. Approve (B) = replay via the normal `Update` / `AddComment` call.\n  Content-type `application/json` (renderer chosen in C's `quarantine show`).\n\nThe proposed content may itself contain the secret ŌĆö that is the point of\nholding it. It is safe because the item lives on the non-syncable quarantine tier.\n\n## A.3 Park logic ŌĆö pure guards, a store primitive, thin boundary glue\n\nThe guards stay pure: `entryguard.Check` / `commentguard.Check` already return the\nfindings (as `*RefusedError`). A new store primitive parks:\n\n- `QuarantineNewEntry(intendedTier, kind, title, body, contentType, findings,\n  author, actorKind) -\u003e (itemID, err)` ŌĆö creates the draft + `q-dest` label.\n- `QuarantineOp(targetID, opKind, content, commentParams, findings, author,\n  actorKind) -\u003e (itemID, err)` ŌĆö creates the intent-item.\n\nBoth open the in-context review question-comment (see A.4). The six write\nboundaries ŌĆö CLI `new`, CLI `update`, CLI `comment`; MCP `remember`, `update`,\n`patch`, `comment` ŌĆö on a would-refuse (findings present, target syncable, not a\nprivate target) call the matching park primitive instead of returning the refusal\nerror. The scan/policy decision stays in the guards; only the OUTCOME branch\nchanges at the boundary.\n\n## A.4 Review thread opened by A (approved deviation from the parent split)\n\nA opens the in-context review question-comment as part of parking, so the item is\nfully review-ready and the findings live in the thread (not duplicated onto the\nitem ŌĆö the native new-entry draft has no clean structured slot for them):\n\n- Held-op intent-item: the question-comment is posted on the LIVE target entry,\n  states the findings (rule + line, never the value), and names the item id\n  (`review: kref quarantine show \u003cid\u003e`).\n- New-entry draft: the question-comment is posted on the draft itself.\n\nThe question is an ordinary question-comment (open until resolved); B resolves it\non approve/reject. Author of the review comment is the system/actor that parked.\n\n## A.5 Result contract\n\nA parked write is NOT an error. It returns, to the writer:\n`quarantined as \u003cid\u003e (N findings) ŌĆö pending human review; see kref quarantine\nshow \u003cid\u003e`. The CLI prints it (exit 0). MCP returns it as a normal, non-`IsError`\ntext result, so an agent treats it as \"held, discuss/await\", not a failure. The\nagent can then answer the reviewer in the thread via `kref_comment`.\n\n## Concurrency (\"normal git stuff\")\n\nParking never conflicts: it appends a new host-local item. The only concurrency\npoint is B's approve-time replay, which goes through the normal write path and so\ninherits the existing layers:\n\n- the per-repo write-lock (flock) serializes concurrent local writers;\n- todo CAS refuses a replay whose target advanced since the op was parked\n  (surfaced as a conflict to re-review, never a clobber);\n- distributed edits merge on pull as usual.\n\nTwo agents parking held-ops for the same target simply create two independent\nitems, each reviewed on its own; replaying both applies them in sequence under\nthe lock, the second conflicting only if it is a stale todo body. No bespoke\nconcurrency machinery is needed in A.\n\n## Out of scope (later sub-projects)\n\n- B: `kref quarantine approve|reject`, op replay / draft retier, thread\n  resolution, `--force` = create+approve, stale-replay conflict handling.\n- C: `kref quarantine list/show`, read-only MCP `kref_quarantine`, pending count\n  in cockpit / `kref stats` / nag, the `quarantine show` renderer.\n\n## Test plan (sketch, finalized in the plan)\n\n- Namespace: quarantine is private-typed, non-syncable (push skips it), hidden\n  from `tier list` and default `list`, rejected as a custom-tier name/type and as\n  a write target.\n- Park, new entry: a flagged `remember`/`new` on a syncable tier creates a draft\n  in quarantine with the right `q-dest` label and a review question-comment on\n  the draft; nothing lands on the intended tier; the writer gets the quarantined\n  result (not an error).\n- Park, held op: a flagged `update`/`patch`/`comment` on a live syncable entry\n  creates an intent-item with a faithful JSON payload and a review comment on the\n  LIVE target; the target head is unchanged.\n- Private target: a flagged write to a private entry is applied as today (no\n  quarantine).\n- Missing scanner: unchanged warn-not-fail (no quarantine; push still backstops).\n- MCP: a flagged MCP write returns a non-`IsError` \"quarantined\" result; no force\n  argument exists.\n\n## Open questions (resolve in the plan)\n\n- The `q-dest` mechanism: a reserved label vs a tiny dedicated field/op. Lean:\n  reserved label, cleared by `retier` in B.\n- Whether `QuarantineNewEntry` and `QuarantineOp` share one primitive with a\n  discriminated intent, or stay two. Lean: two, thin.\n- Exact JSON schema + a `schema` version tag for the intent-item body.\n"},{"type":9,"timestamp":1784142485,"nonce":"G31NqCkSkD2PvZwMyMe+Qslut08=","label":"area:design"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1784142485,"nonce":"7Y/r2G3cInc30LYrEEFkkIqJye0=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"create"},{"type":5,"timestamp":1784142491,"nonce":"TGcjoJNWQC4S+1R501pZHbNcRHE=","to":"4cb93aef761159f5bd4fa90b1f726d557fcf57e7402887e93fa87abfb9f1fb30","link_type":"derived-from"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1784144640,"nonce":"REKGPUGb/U1t0RJOU4zi2x+nXug=","body":"# Quarantine review ŌĆö sub-project A: namespace + item model + park-on-write (design)\n\nStatus: design approved 2026-07-15 (Trevor). Sub-project of the quarantine-review\narc; parent design `kref show 4cb93aef7611`. This spec covers ONLY A. B (review +\napprove/reject + replay) and C (surfaces) are separate own-cycle sub-projects.\n\n## Scope\n\nA flagged write (a body/comment tripping betterleaks on a syncable tier) is\nDIVERTED into a reserved holding namespace as a review-ready item, with its\nin-context review thread opened ŌĆö instead of being refused. A stops there:\nnothing is applied to the live target, and approve/reject/replay is B.\n\nDeliverable: after A, every flagged write across all six boundaries lands in the\n`quarantine` namespace with enough payload for B to apply it, and a reviewer can\nsee (via the thread) that a review is pending. `entryguard`/`commentguard` keep\nscanning; their OUTCOME changes from refuse to park.\n\n## A.1 The `quarantine` namespace\n\nA new reserved, private-typed built-in tier `quarantine` (`refs/kref-quarantine/`):\n\n- Added to `reservedTierNames`; not selectable as a write target and not a valid\n  custom-tier type.\n- Private-typed =\u003e non-syncable by construction (never pushed; push already skips\n  private, and must also skip quarantine).\n- Hidden from `kref tier list` and from normal entry listings (a system tier);\n  reachable only through the quarantine surfaces (built in C) and by direct id.\n- Writes into it are allowed by the secret policy (private tier =\u003e no scan), so\n  parking a secret-bearing payload cannot re-trigger parking (no recursion).\n\nBecause it is private-typed, quarantine items are host-local: they never merge\nacross machines. Each host has its own review queue; only APPROVED writes\n(replayed onto syncable entries in B) travel via normal DAG pull.\n\n### A.1.1 Reserved name, existing repos, and conflicts\n\nReserved-name prevention is AUTO-HANDLED by adding `quarantine` to\n`entry.reservedTierNames` (alongside adding it to `BuiltinTierDefs`). The\nexisting validation then covers every path with no new guarding:\n\n- `Store.TierAdd` calls `entry.ValidateTierName` before writing config, so\n  `kref tier add quarantine` is rejected up front.\n- `resolveTiers` re-validates every `kref.tier.*` key on open and skips any\n  reserved discovered `refs/kref-*` namespace, so a foreign `quarantine` ref\n  arriving via fetch is ignored (and is anyway the built-in's own namespace).\n\nExisting repos need NO migration. Built-in tiers come from `BuiltinTierDefs()`,\nmerged in `resolveTiers` on every `store.Open`, so every repo ŌĆö new or existing,\nthis one included ŌĆö has `quarantine` the moment the code ships. The\n`refs/kref-quarantine/` namespace materializes lazily on the first park write,\nexactly as the other built-ins do; there is nothing to create.\n\nThe one real conflict: a repo that ALREADY declared a custom tier named\n`quarantine` (legal until now, since the name was not reserved). Once `quarantine`\nis reserved, `resolveTiers` would treat that `kref.tier.quarantine` config key as\ninvalid and hard-fail the open ŌĆö and because the store cannot open, `kref tier rm`\ncannot run to fix it. Policy (Trevor to confirm; near-zero pre-release): DETECT\nthe colliding key on open and fail with a targeted, actionable error that names\nthe exact escape (`git config --unset kref.tier.quarantine`) and notes that\nentries under `refs/kref-quarantine/` are now the reserved system tier and how to\nmove them out. Chosen over auto-migrating the user's tier (heavier: config +\n`refs/kref-quarantine/*` rewrite) and over soft-skip-and-shadow (silently\nreinterprets their old data as the private-typed system tier). The detection is a\nsmall, explicit check in `resolveTiers` that upgrades the generic \"reserved\" error\nto this specific guidance when the reserved key is `quarantine`.\n\n## A.2 Item model ŌĆö two natural forms, one namespace\n\nHeld-write is stored as INTENT and replayed on approval (B) through the normal\nstore write path, so CAS, the write-lock, provenance, and every normal guard run\nat apply-time and an approved write looks exactly like a fresh human write.\n\n- New entry (`kref_remember` / `kref new`): born as a real draft entry in\n  `quarantine` with its proposed kind/title/body/content-type, plus a reserved\n  `q-dest:\u003ctier\u003e` label naming its intended destination tier. The review thread\n  is anchored on the draft. Approve (B) = `retier` the draft to `\u003ctier\u003e` ŌĆö the id\n  and the review thread travel with it. (A fresh create on approval would orphan\n  the thread; retier preserves it. This is why new entries are draft-native.)\n\n- Update / patch / comment on a live syncable entry: a `kind:quarantine`\n  intent-item whose body is a structured JSON record:\n  `{schema, target_id, op_kind: set-body|add-comment, content, comment: {question?,\n  reply_to?}, author, actor_kind, time}`. The live target is untouched and stays\n  syncable. Approve (B) = replay via the normal `Update` / `AddComment` call.\n  Content-type `application/json` (renderer chosen in C's `quarantine show`).\n\nThe proposed content may itself contain the secret ŌĆö that is the point of\nholding it. It is safe because the item lives on the non-syncable quarantine tier.\n\n## A.3 Park logic ŌĆö pure guards, a store primitive, thin boundary glue\n\nThe guards stay pure: `entryguard.Check` / `commentguard.Check` already return the\nfindings (as `*RefusedError`). A new store primitive parks:\n\n- `QuarantineNewEntry(intendedTier, kind, title, body, contentType, findings,\n  author, actorKind) -\u003e (itemID, err)` ŌĆö creates the draft + `q-dest` label.\n- `QuarantineOp(targetID, opKind, content, commentParams, findings, author,\n  actorKind) -\u003e (itemID, err)` ŌĆö creates the intent-item.\n\nBoth open the in-context review question-comment (see A.4). The six write\nboundaries ŌĆö CLI `new`, CLI `update`, CLI `comment`; MCP `remember`, `update`,\n`patch`, `comment` ŌĆö on a would-refuse (findings present, target syncable, not a\nprivate target) call the matching park primitive instead of returning the refusal\nerror. The scan/policy decision stays in the guards; only the OUTCOME branch\nchanges at the boundary.\n\n## A.4 Review thread opened by A (approved deviation from the parent split)\n\nA opens the in-context review question-comment as part of parking, so the item is\nfully review-ready and the findings live in the thread (not duplicated onto the\nitem ŌĆö the native new-entry draft has no clean structured slot for them):\n\n- Held-op intent-item: the question-comment is posted on the LIVE target entry,\n  states the findings (rule + line, never the value), and names the item id\n  (`review: kref quarantine show \u003cid\u003e`).\n- New-entry draft: the question-comment is posted on the draft itself.\n\nThe question is an ordinary question-comment (open until resolved); B resolves it\non approve/reject. Author of the review comment is the system/actor that parked.\n\n## A.5 Result contract\n\nA parked write is NOT an error. It returns, to the writer:\n`quarantined as \u003cid\u003e (N findings) ŌĆö pending human review; see kref quarantine\nshow \u003cid\u003e`. The CLI prints it (exit 0). MCP returns it as a normal, non-`IsError`\ntext result, so an agent treats it as \"held, discuss/await\", not a failure. The\nagent can then answer the reviewer in the thread via `kref_comment`.\n\n## Concurrency (\"normal git stuff\")\n\nParking never conflicts: it appends a new host-local item. The only concurrency\npoint is B's approve-time replay, which goes through the normal write path and so\ninherits the existing layers:\n\n- the per-repo write-lock (flock) serializes concurrent local writers;\n- todo CAS refuses a replay whose target advanced since the op was parked\n  (surfaced as a conflict to re-review, never a clobber);\n- distributed edits merge on pull as usual.\n\nTwo agents parking held-ops for the same target simply create two independent\nitems, each reviewed on its own; replaying both applies them in sequence under\nthe lock, the second conflicting only if it is a stale todo body. No bespoke\nconcurrency machinery is needed in A.\n\n## Out of scope (later sub-projects)\n\n- B: `kref quarantine approve|reject`, op replay / draft retier, thread\n  resolution, `--force` = create+approve, stale-replay conflict handling.\n- C: `kref quarantine list/show`, read-only MCP `kref_quarantine`, pending count\n  in cockpit / `kref stats` / nag, the `quarantine show` renderer.\n\n## Test plan (sketch, finalized in the plan)\n\n- Namespace: quarantine is private-typed, non-syncable (push skips it), hidden\n  from `tier list` and default `list`, rejected as a custom-tier name/type and as\n  a write target.\n- Park, new entry: a flagged `remember`/`new` on a syncable tier creates a draft\n  in quarantine with the right `q-dest` label and a review question-comment on\n  the draft; nothing lands on the intended tier; the writer gets the quarantined\n  result (not an error).\n- Park, held op: a flagged `update`/`patch`/`comment` on a live syncable entry\n  creates an intent-item with a faithful JSON payload and a review comment on the\n  LIVE target; the target head is unchanged.\n- Private target: a flagged write to a private entry is applied as today (no\n  quarantine).\n- Missing scanner: unchanged warn-not-fail (no quarantine; push still backstops).\n- MCP: a flagged MCP write returns a non-`IsError` \"quarantined\" result; no force\n  argument exists.\n\n## Open questions (resolve in the plan)\n\n- The `q-dest` mechanism: a reserved label vs a tiny dedicated field/op. Lean:\n  reserved label, cleared by `retier` in B.\n- Whether `QuarantineNewEntry` and `QuarantineOp` share one primitive with a\n  discriminated intent, or stay two. Lean: two, thin.\n- Exact JSON schema + a `schema` version tag for the intent-item body.\n"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1784224330,"nonce":"9TfHfUfI7PT0E2Z2aDlXdsPMMCM=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"retier"}]}